column1: Before 1 January 2020, will the U.S. President sign legislation increasing the number of exemptions for autonomous vehicles allowed per manufacturer by the Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards?
column6: ['Technology', 'US Policy']
column11: A motor vehicle manufacturer may petition the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration for an exemption for self-driving vehicles without human controls (The Fuse, Cornell Law). There is legislation under consideration that would increase the number of exemptions U.S. regulators are able to grant per manufacturer (S.1885 AV START Act, H.R.3388 - SELF DRIVE Act). Proponents say it would liberate innovation for self-driving vehicles while opponents say that it would place consumers under undue risk (Consumer Reports, Tom's Hardware, Competitive Enterprise Institute). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

This is probably not going to rise above the static of the next year. In the coming month, the CR expires Dec 7, so Congress will have to pass a budget or kick the can with another CR. Based on the last 20 years, they will likely pass another short-term CR until about Jan 18 (MLK Day is Jan 21, so it buys Congress an extra 3 days with minimal impact in case they can't pass a budget or CR). Looking back and doing the calculations my self, the average CR length is 110 days (excluding 3 years with full-year CRs - including that data increases the CR length to 140 days). Conveniently, 110 days this year falls on Friday, Jan 18. So there's that.

I agree with @patrickmeehan5 's point about an easy bi-partisan gesture. So I think there will be an increase in the exemptions at some point, so the key to the question is whether it will happen in the specified time frame. https://www.quora.com/How-long-does-it-take-to-pass-a-bill-in-the-US Although the top answer here is right to state that there are of course very diverse reasons why some bills take longer or don't pass into law at all, the median and average times it took from introduction to becoming law are less than a year (215 and 263 days, respectively). Since this bill has been around for some time and has some support, I think it is fairly likely it will become a law in the specified timeframe.
